The study indicates that there are many differences in the beginning of couple life and the number of children, whether or not the woman works and the type of occupied employment.
Those who do not have activities outside of the home, work part-time or have a little stable job, get married earlier, have their first pregnancy earlier and have more children.
On the contrary, women with stable employment, mainly in the public sector, reject entry into couple life and first pregnancy, and have fewer children.
Women between 35 and 49 years of age have their first child, on average, 3.7 years after having been coupled. This figure is up to 4.1 in those working in the public sector. “These data show that women with stable employment needed more time in their lives to get it, which led them to reject the union and arrival of children.
In addition, the type of employment exercised has a large influence on maternity, but less the date of starting common life,” explains CSIC researcher Margarita Delgado.
The level of study is another factor that increases the gap of the age of women's marriage and their first child.
According to the survey, the higher the level of training, the more they marry and have their first child late.
The difference is also between women of the same generation.
For example, in the 35-49-year-old group, those who conducted primary and higher studies were mothers for the first time at 25.1 and 32.1 years of age.
“A different dispute also occurs among women, depending on their level of study.
