As this took place with the ABS brake anti-blocking system and as this will take place with ESP stability control, emergency brake aid systems will constitute a mandatory element on European cars.
They are already mandatory for newly registered tourist vehicles and light commercial vehicles, while for the rest of the vehicles a shortage period was established by the end of February 2011.
The measures imposed by the European Union are aimed at strengthening the protection of pedestrians, although by its means of action it can also contribute to avoiding many retreat shocks.
The emergency brake assistant acts by increasing the pressure on the brakes in the event of emergency detected by the system thanks to the foot strike given by the driver.
But the latter does not always keep the pressure until the end.
According to a study conducted by the car component manufacturer Bosch, one-third of the drivers involved in an accident had not been able to push the brake before the collision, and half of them had not benefited from all its strength.
Up to 1100 accidents
The intervention of the aid, on the other hand, requires the maximum brake system, reducing the distance the car needs to stop.
According to a EU study, if all cars were equipped with this type of elements, up to 1,100 deadly accidents in which pedestrians are involved could be avoided every year.
This reduction would be even more important with the popularization of the so-called smart emergency brake systems: it is calculated that a disaster in four with wounded would be avoided.
In this case, the vehicle is equipped with a system that, thanks to a radar or a camera, detects obstacles and prevents the driver from acting slightly on the brakes.
If the driver reacts, it helps to increase the pressure on the pedal, if necessary.
If it does not react, and although the collision is inevitable, the device exercises the maximum effort on the brakes to minimize damage.
